            <h1>Temperature</h1>

<div class="page" id="page1">
      <p>
        The temperature of an object is defined as the average (translational) kinetic energy of its particles (molecules
        and atoms). The kinetic energy of each particle is related to both the mass of the particle and the speed of the
        particle.
      </p>
      <p class="text-centered">
        Kinetic energy is defined as: KE (particle) = 1/2*m*v<sup>2</sup>
      </p>
      <p>
        The temperature of an object is defined as the average of (1/2*m*v<sup>2</sup>) for all of the object's
        particles.
      </p>
      <p>
        So, if something causes the particles of an object to start moving around faster, the temperature increases.
        But if something causes the particles of an object start to slow, the temperature decreases.
      </p>
    </div>

